Amanda KhozaNew eThekwini mayor Zandile Gumede. (Amanda Khoza, News24) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Durban - EThekwini Mayor, Zandile Gumede, and outgoing city manager, Sibusiso Sithole, have denied that there were tensions between them, the city said in a statement.During a joint media briefing at the Durban City Hall on Thursday, Gumede said Sithole had &ldquo;not been suspended or forced out of office as purported in the media&rdquo;.According to a Daily News report Gumede slapped Sithole with a letter instructing him to take &ldquo;compulsory leave&rdquo; until the end of his contract on December 31. He confirmed to the paper that he received the letter and that he had allegedly been told to &ldquo;leave with immediate effect&rdquo;.&ldquo;However, the City Manager will conclude his duties on 23 December 2016 to allow for continuity through an acting appointment by a special Council meeting, until such time as a permanent appointment is made,&rdquo; Gumede said. Gumede thanked Sithole for his contribution towards developing the Metro. &ldquo;Both the City Manager and I would like to assure the public and city employees that the cohesion that exists within the Metro management will ensure a smooth transitional period.&rdquo;Dumisile Nene, the city&rsquo;s deputy city manager for corporate and human resources cluster, would act as the City Manager for three months or until the position is permanently filled.&ldquo;The process to fill the position of the city manager has started. As per a decision taken at an in-committee Council meeting today, a recruitment agency will assist with filling the position to ensure the process is fair,&rdquo; Gumede said.Sithole was one of the candidates who had applied for the position, the city said.&nbsp;24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.